A transiliac bone biopsy specimen was obtained following two three-day courses of tetracycline, separated by 14 days. The specimen was fixed in neutral phosphate-buffered formaldehyde solution, embedded in methyl methacrylate2) and sectioned at 5mm using a Jung Model K Sledge Microtome (Heidelberg, Germany). Sections were stained with modified Masson, and Goldner, and histomorphometric analysis was performed with a Merz-Schenk Integrating Eyepiece.3) The following parameters were measured in trabecular bone as previously described:
% total bone volume, or % of medullary space occupied by bone matrix;
% relative osteoid volume, or % of bone matrix composed of osteoid (unmineralized matrix);
% total osteoid surface, or % of trabecular surface covered by osteoid;
% osteoblastic osteoid surface, or % of trabecular surface covered by osteoid lined by characteristic osteoblasts;
mean osteoid seam width;
number of osteoclasts/mm medullary space;
% total resorptive surface, or % of trabecular surface containing scalloped resorptive bays (How-ship’s lacunae);
% osteoclastic resorptive surface, or % of trabecular surface in apposition to osteoclasts; and
% fibrotic surface, or % trabecular surface in apposition to marrow fibrosis.
